"Heinrich I., Gärtner H., Monbaron M.","Tension wood formed in Fagus sylvatica and Alnus glutinosa after simulated mass movement events",2007,"IAWA Journal","28","1",,"39","48",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33847209973&partnerID=40&md5=a50d492b496f54844c3bc342a0b71f82","Department of Geosciences, Geography, University of Fribourg, 1700 Fribourg, Switzerland; Swiss Federal Research Institute WSL, Zürcherstrasse 111, 8903 Birmensdorf, Switzerland; ICG-V, Research Centre Jülich GmbH, Wilhelm-Johnen-Str., 52325 Jülich, Germany","Heinrich, I., Department of Geosciences, Geography, University of Fribourg, 1700 Fribourg, Switzerland, ICG-V, Research Centre Jülich GmbH, Wilhelm-Johnen-Str., 52325 Jülich, Germany; Gärtner, H., Swiss Federal Research Institute WSL, Zürcherstrasse 111, 8903 Birmensdorf, Switzerland; Monbaron, M., Department of Geosciences, Geography, University of Fribourg, 1700 Fribourg, Switzerland","Due to the likelihood of global climate change, the frequency and magnitude of natural hazards such as mass movements may likewise change, thus favouring the refinement of methods to detect and quantify geomorphic events when precise records are not available. Geomorphic events typically have a significant effect on tree growth, e.g., reaction wood marked by changes in ring widths and wood density. To date, several dendroecological techniques have been developed to document the occurrence of these events but it rarely has been possible to retrieve additional information from reaction wood concerning the precise kind and intensity of geomorphic events. Additional qualitative information inferred from reaction wood of trees holds the potential to not only document but also estimate important characteristics of natural hazard events. To refine the methods already used in dendrogeomorpology, experiments simulating various geomorphic events were used to monitor subsequent wood anatomical responses of Fagus sylvatica and Alnus glutinosa. The preliminary results indicate that these two common broadleaf tree species show variations in their reactions to different experimental treatments.","Geomorphic process; Puncher samples; Reaction wood; Wood anatomy","Alnus; Alnus glutinosa; Fagus; Fagus sylvatica",,,,,,"Alestalo, J., (1971) Dendrochronological interpretation of geomorphic processes. Fennia, 105. , Helsinki; Arganbright, D.G., Bensend, D.W., Relationship of gelatinous fiber development to tree lean in soft maple (1968) Wood Science, 1, pp. 37-40; Bland, D.E., Scurfield, G., The chemistry of reaction wood. Part IV. The distribution and nature of the lignin in seedlings of hardwoods (1964) Holzforschung, 18, pp. 161-166; Burns, G.P., Eccentric growth and the formation of redwood in the main stem of conifers (1920) Vt. Agr. Sta. Bull, 219, pp. 1-16; Chow, K.Y., A comparative study of the structure and chemical composition of tension wood and normal wood in beech (Fagus sylvatica L.) (1946) Forestry, 20, pp. 62-77; Clague, J.J., Souther, J.G., The dusty creek landslide on Mount Cayley, British Columbia (1982) Can. J. Earth Sci, 19, pp. 524-539; Clair, B., Thibaut, B., Shrinkage of the gelatinous layer of poplar and beech tension wood (2001) IAWA J, 22, pp. 121-131; Cleveland, W.S. 1994. The elements of graphing data. Hobart Press, Summit, NJCook, R.D., Weisberg, S., (1999) Applied regression including computing and graphics, , John Wiley & Sons, Hoboken, NJ; Côté, W.A., Day Jr., A.C., Anatomy and ultrastructure of reaction wood (1965) Cellular ultrastructure of woody plants, pp. 391-418. , W. A. Côté ed, Syracuse University Press, Syracuse, NY; Forster, T., Schweingruber, F.H., Denneler, B., Increment puncher: A tool for extracting small cores of wood and bark from living trees (2000) IAWA J, 21, pp. 169-180; Gärtner, H., Stoffel, M., Lièvre, I., Monbaron, M., Tree ring analyses and detailed geomorphological mapping on a forested debris flow cone in Switzerland (2003) Debris flow hazards mitigation: Mechan